{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"08a76590b2257178","type":"text","text":"Related to ideas from Lada Kesseler.\n\nPossible match: **Instruction sandwich** (wrap critical constraints around the task so they’re less likely to get skipped).\n\nSource: [Lada Kesseler patterns](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M-zOSEJFNos)","x":-1200,"y":2658,"width":250,"height":223},
		{"id":"7f30a69bc7173cb8","type":"text","text":"- **Skills.sh**: referenced as a popular context/package distribution option.\n\nSource: [Context as code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlC7jq4ooSM)","x":-1200,"y":2228,"width":250,"height":100},
		{"id":"af5612bc47d483d0","type":"text","text":"**Feedback as a first-class engineering concern**: optimize for fast, reliable signals, not just faster code generation.\n\nSource: [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A)","x":-300,"y":1956,"width":250,"height":232},
		{"id":"42fc6254bc932949","type":"text","text":"**Purpose gate (persistent widget):** ask the user for the agent’s purpose at startup, keep it visible, and append it into the system prompt for steerability.\n\nSource: [Pi coding agent](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f8cfH5XX-XU)","x":700,"y":-130,"width":250,"height":170},
		{"id":"c71d0a0f2f2ac5b6","type":"text","text":"**Engineer the loop**\nRoles • Context • Feedback • Boundaries\n\nTreat agentic work like systems engineering: define roles, bound reach, version context, and design fast validation.\n\nKey sources: [Context as code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlC7jq4ooSM) · [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A) · [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-250,"y":-1340,"width":460,"height":220},
		{"id":"8fbd9c5f6a9f7542","type":"text","text":"I experienced it with a human developer when I explained everything to him and he made some assumptions and went for work for one day and then came back with something that completely was different from what we discussed or at least I thought I was communicating So we had to rethink everything. Example of overengineering and certainly AI assistants can do something like that as well. But we all should aim for shorter feedback loops.","x":120,"y":-507,"width":401,"height":288},
		{"id":"48e27c9352b86bb7","type":"text","text":"**Context as “new code” (metaphor)**: context should meet expectations we have for code (correctness, performance, reuse, automation).\n\nSource: [Context as code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlC7jq4ooSM)","x":-1200,"y":1470,"width":320,"height":240},
		{"id":"2d9f3ed8fba515f4","type":"text","text":"My comment: this is so obvious to me that I would not even put it as a node, but really I think this must be a node because I've noticed that for example, For example, Kiro from AWS creates its own dot Kiro folder as if it should be git ignored potentially but really context is a new code So it's related to that video as well. and yes, I think I think all the context related documents must be version controlled.","x":-780,"y":1260,"width":428,"height":247},
		{"id":"50db77df50320dfd","type":"file","file":"notes/Interview-Driven Specification.md","x":-300,"y":-780,"width":372,"height":80,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"817f48750e67c16a","type":"text","text":"In general I think at some point I was thinking about different mental models how to think about agents. So maybe we can start doing that.","x":700,"y":1130,"width":250,"height":184,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"4bc892c31dcf1e23","type":"text","text":"**PIV loops over “big bang” builds**: Slice the PRD into phases and run plan/implement/validate per phase.\n\nSource: [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-300,"y":-305,"width":320,"height":91,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"ba344e856c29a3af","type":"file","file":"notes/Spec Branch Flow.md","x":-300,"y":66,"width":381,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"2028adc7b0315a3c","type":"text","text":"Git-related patterns","x":-300,"y":-34,"width":250,"height":60,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"dc5cfd3c5a97928f","type":"text","text":"yes this is a good idea and I lately try to do detailed enough commit messages and I do notice that from time to time I go back in history using agents to do analysis, So, in general it is a good pattern. Overall we can create Git related patterns for AI assisted software development. and one of them can be already existing spec branch flow. And this particular pattern I can call something different, not just commit message transitization, but something about really capturing measuring the summaries for future references.","x":120,"y":-159,"width":403,"height":297},
		{"id":"cdd8b6fb04eac0ab","type":"text","text":"**Commit-message standardization**: Treat commit messages as structured summaries the agent can leverage later during “prime”.\n\nSource: [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-300,"y":-174,"width":365,"height":100,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"179c2331b2326908","type":"text","text":"Agentic Discovery (or Search)\n\nSource: [RAG for codebases](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=60G93MXT4DI)","x":-1200,"y":-810,"width":304,"height":90,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"4bab4d6fa0482e42","type":"text","text":"- **Structural overviews / “repo maps”**: a precomputed map of the repo (files + key symbols) so the agent can quickly narrow where to look; described as built from parsing (e.g., Tree-sitter) rather than embeddings.\n\nSource: [RAG for codebases](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=60G93MXT4DI)","x":-1200,"y":-680,"width":420,"height":152,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"25116005a7557fe5","type":"text","text":"Bridging strategy: let the agent choose retrieval per query\n\nSource: [RAG for codebases](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=60G93MXT4DI)","x":-1200,"y":-488,"width":250,"height":143,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"6f909454debfe1c3","type":"text","text":"**Team principles (as described):**\n  - Underfund projects slightly to force clarity and leverage automation.\n  - Bias to shipping *today*; speed compounds via shorter feedback loops.\n  - Give engineers “unlimited tokens” early to explore; optimize costs only after something works at scale.\n\nSource: [Boris Cherny (Claude Code)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=We7BZVKbCVw)","x":700,"y":1650,"width":449,"height":270},
		{"id":"4ab463af68e42464","type":"text","text":"Human aspects of AI-assisted software development","x":700,"y":1354,"width":391,"height":64,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"99cb2b5b1f5dfd8d","type":"text","text":"Good point, even though context engineering is important, and tooling may be as important as well.","x":-780,"y":-780,"width":320,"height":118},
		{"id":"4900db7db2f8f78e","type":"text","text":"**Latent demand, two ways**\n- *User latent demand:* repeated hacks/misuse show what people want the product to be.\n- *Model latent demand:* observe what the model “wants to do” when given minimal scaffolding, then shape tools and interfaces around that.\n\nSource: [Boris Cherny (Claude Code)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=We7BZVKbCVw)","x":700,"y":2160,"width":422,"height":248,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"bc57200a7bad3b2d","type":"text","text":"This is something that I'm thinking about when building some minimal agents to control some projects and keep adding more functionality via tools, observing what kind of functionality they would need and maybe even asking them what they would need.","x":1120,"y":960,"width":366,"height":181},
		{"id":"9f813b9f6c88ee47","type":"text","text":"people as tools An agent may say that it needs something to be done, and create a task for a human someone. And that may be part of its context that it can do something like that. And one One way to evolve such agentic systems The first thing is to see if such tasks can be picked up by some tools or by other agents in the future and automated.","x":700,"y":2548,"width":424,"height":209},
		{"id":"6c80bc446d305d50","type":"text","text":"People as Tools","x":700,"y":2458,"width":250,"height":60,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"e3c2b41b1a2c8d40","type":"text","text":"- **Tessl**: used as an example platform for context validation/evals/registry.\n\nSource: [Context as code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlC7jq4ooSM)","x":-1200,"y":1985,"width":360,"height":203},
		{"id":"231e5a384d4917c2","type":"text","text":"**Trust, but verify (with a validation pyramid)**\nImplementation is delegated to the agent, but bounded by a plan up-front and a validation strategy after; automated checks reduce effort, but human review and manual testing still remain part of “done”.\n\nSource: [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-300,"y":1270,"width":314,"height":271,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"20b0646990fc134f","type":"text","text":"**Assumption management beats code review**\nA recurring claim is that many agent mistakes come from mismatched expectations rather than syntactically bad code; the workflow counteracts this with explicit Q&A during planning and by translating conversation into a structured spec.\n\nSource: [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-300,"y":-610,"width":380,"height":265,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"9d92982eff315404","type":"text","text":"- **Role blur:** engineering/design/PM roles increasingly overlap; “builder” becomes a plausible umbrella role (with specialties rather than strict boundaries).\n\nSource: [Boris Cherny (Claude Code)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=We7BZVKbCVw)","x":700,"y":1458,"width":400,"height":152,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"130b38b75bff3e92","type":"text","text":"**Automation over inspection**: tests and checks provide repeatable verification; reading is (at best) a heuristic.\n\nSource: [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A)","x":-300,"y":1581,"width":250,"height":239},
		{"id":"1d2d90f8038b7d20","type":"text","text":"- **“Tech lead for agents”**: the human’s job becomes setting standards, providing context, and reviewing outcomes—less “typing code,” more “ensuring good code can be written.”\n\nSource: [Context as code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlC7jq4ooSM)","x":-1200,"y":1750,"width":325,"height":195},
		{"id":"632a4444ec699f03","type":"text","text":"**Planning & Specs**\nAssumption reduction, structured prompts, and repeatable workflows.","x":-300,"y":-920,"width":320,"height":110,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"08aa864b24729a7b","type":"text","text":"**Org & Human Dynamics**\nHow teams, roles, and human-in-the-loop responsibilities shift.","x":700,"y":820,"width":320,"height":110,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"1e19a4480731bc70","type":"file","file":"notes/Context Hygiene.md","x":-1200,"y":960,"width":340,"height":60,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"9d4d0cf2b962db3e","type":"file","file":"notes/Maker-Checker Pattern.md","x":700,"y":-670,"width":340,"height":50,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"86f13afb74e3581c","type":"text","text":"**Reach vs control (autonomy ↔ isolation)**\nAlways-on / everywhere agents increase reach *and* blast radius; sandboxing/isolation is the counterweight.\n\nSource: [OpenClaw vs Claude Code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9f38h_GooA8)","x":700,"y":-560,"width":360,"height":180,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"fcb2fa8967768d7a","type":"text","text":"**Evidence-first code review (evidence bundles)**\nPrefer runnable proof (tests, screenshots, click paths) over “read the diff and hope”.\n\nSources: [OpenAI Codex app](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AFHiiL-ZKms) · [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A)","x":-300,"y":1070,"width":360,"height":160,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"6998308f4612a763","type":"text","text":"**Capability discovery loop (tools from observed needs)**\nStart minimal, watch what humans/agents keep asking for, then add the smallest tool that removes that friction.\n\nSource: [Boris Cherny (Claude Code)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=We7BZVKbCVw)","x":700,"y":1960,"width":360,"height":160,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"6649bb73473318c2","type":"text","text":"**Mental models for agents**\nA note to collect: intern vs contractor vs tool vs teammate vs system operator (and what each implies).","x":700,"y":960,"width":360,"height":130,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"ff8e99e37ab9ece4","type":"text","text":"**Task-scoped contexts (thread per role)**\nSwitch context when the *job changes* (build vs review vs investigate), not just when you feel stuck.\n\nSources: [Lada Kesseler patterns](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M-zOSEJFNos) · [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-1880,"y":1458,"width":360,"height":160,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"7f71f5b91487dcaa","type":"text","text":"- **AI Layer in the repo**: Keep PRD/specs, global rules, commands, and reference docs as explicit versioned assets.\n\nSource: [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-1919,"y":2311,"width":399,"height":150,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"e10182efba073246","type":"text","text":"Generalist vs. Specialist Agents\n\nSource: [Lada Kesseler patterns](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M-zOSEJFNos)","x":-1844,"y":2566,"width":250,"height":60,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"81fae88598d44b6e","type":"text","text":"\"There are many coding agents, but this one is mine.\"\n\nSource: [Pi coding agent](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f8cfH5XX-XU)","x":1480,"y":-825,"width":280,"height":115},
		{"id":"378e8c6db6384d81","type":"text","text":"**Agent Architecture**\nRole separation, boundaries, and UI/UX for supervising agent work.","x":700,"y":-975,"width":320,"height":110,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"a4fbe1f0dc083201","type":"file","file":"notes/Sandboxing AI Agents.md","x":1260,"y":-542,"width":340,"height":57,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"56c27916b0905e5a","type":"text","text":"**Evidence-First Review (Evidence Bundles)**","x":280,"y":1499,"width":300,"height":70,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"27e0f7a8625541cd","type":"text","text":"- **Daily change digest:** a scheduled report grouped by theme so a maintainer can track what merged without reading everything (as described).\n\nSource: [OpenAI Codex app](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AFHiiL-ZKms)","x":1760,"y":543,"width":560,"height":135,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"9352d872b4773716","type":"text","text":"- **Steering during execution:** “midterm steering” implies workflows where you continuously redirect work rather than restarting tasks.\n\nSource: [OpenAI Codex app](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AFHiiL-ZKms)","x":1303,"y":360,"width":460,"height":130,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"c50373404824ff3a","type":"text","text":"- **Command-center UI for agents:** treat agent work as a supervised system-of-systems, not a single chat thread or a single IDE surface.\n\nSource: [OpenAI Codex app](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AFHiiL-ZKms)","x":870,"y":225,"width":420,"height":135,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"6bd12d082ea19e2e","type":"text","text":"**Adversarial collaboration (inside one system)**\nExplicitly assigning “expand” vs “critique” roles creates productive tension and can reduce premature convergence.\n\nSource: [Claude Code agent teams](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=y_W3486ccfI)","x":850,"y":506,"width":340,"height":172,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"00712fd5c3d23d1b","type":"text","text":"**Isolate always-on agents**\n\nSource: [OpenClaw vs Claude Code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9f38h_GooA8)","x":1513,"y":-305,"width":250,"height":135},
		{"id":"9065cd779f3f3a77","type":"text","text":"**Context & Guidance**\nTreat context like an asset: version it, scope it, and keep it readable.","x":-1350,"y":700,"width":320,"height":110,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"a248b4589672508d","type":"text","text":"**Validation & Feedback**\nSampling rate, evidence, CI, and other fast correctness signals.","x":-370,"y":760,"width":320,"height":110,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"31bd5e09fe77845b","type":"text","text":"**Discovery & Retrieval**\nSearch/retrieval strategies that keep context cheap and debuggable.","x":-1216,"y":-1100,"width":320,"height":110,"color":"6"},
		{"id":"da63045df2ce5bb0","type":"file","file":"notes/Thin Slices and Tight Loops.md","x":-906,"y":630,"width":340,"height":70,"color":"2"},
		{"id":"c89f29ef51b8d90e","type":"text","text":"**“Don’t box the model in”:** prefer a goal + tools over rigid orchestrations; let the model pull context via tools instead of front-loading it.\n\nSource: [Boris Cherny (Claude Code)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=We7BZVKbCVw)","x":-1203,"y":-305,"width":426,"height":95,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"ab9aa745422bf5d2","type":"text","text":"What would be a good note to create in the documents?","x":-840,"y":2821,"width":250,"height":60,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"493fa6443e6e2be8","type":"text","text":"**Non-determinism forces repetition**: run scenarios multiple times and evaluate averages instead of trusting a single run.\n\nSource: [Context as code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlC7jq4ooSM)","x":-300,"y":3420,"width":250,"height":194},
		{"id":"c204947851b81ea7","type":"text","text":"- **Frequent integration**: keep branches short-lived to avoid lowering the feedback frequency.\n\nSource: [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A)","x":-300,"y":3240,"width":250,"height":132},
		{"id":"1d2bcf3e689225f0","type":"text","text":"- **Behavioral tests as invariants**: use tests that express domain rules so AI changes are constrained by outcomes.\n\nSource: [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A)","x":-300,"y":2960,"width":250,"height":254},
		{"id":"90390134991534f8","type":"text","text":"- **Small-chunk AI usage**: ask for smaller changes and validate each one quickly.\n\nSource: [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A)","x":40,"y":2649,"width":250,"height":202},
		{"id":"2d7628f1c0b43cd0","type":"text","text":"- **Sampling rate (analogy)**: validation frequency must scale with change frequency.\n\nSource: [AI programming assistants](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XavrebMKH2A)","x":-425,"y":2377,"width":250,"height":222},
		{"id":"e403e42dd121b239","type":"text","text":"**Split the roles**\n\nSource: [OpenClaw vs Claude Code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9f38h_GooA8)","x":700,"y":-305,"width":250,"height":120},
		{"id":"a9f6c5a0c96837d5","type":"text","text":"**Specialization as differentiation:** use specialist agents/teams/chains to avoid “generic” outputs (as argued).\n\nSource: [Pi coding agent](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f8cfH5XX-XU)","x":521,"y":170,"width":250,"height":190},
		{"id":"ebd97f51dea6031b","type":"text","text":"I should create this node, but maybe it can be even more general. it's not only generalist and specialist it's really like specialists for specific tasks. tasks. It's worth doing different tasks in different threads like code review but here intuition is really important because sometimes maybe the same task can be still continued, a different task still can be continued in the same context but if it's really like a different view on the problem it may be worth creating a separate context and give a different guidance to an agent","x":-2440,"y":1956,"width":406,"height":311},
		{"id":"9327540fd40f1ae3","type":"text","text":"**Version-Controlled Context (Docs as Code)**","x":-2440,"y":890,"width":300,"height":70,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"2fd1e8604e8c67a4","type":"text","text":"**Task-Scoped Contexts (Thread per Role)**","x":-2590,"y":1314,"width":300,"height":70,"color":"3"},
		{"id":"b0c9a8d0583e1e57","type":"text","text":"**Version-controlled context documents**\nTreat agent guidance (rules, docs, examples) as repo assets: diffable, reviewable, and pinned to reality.\n\nSources: [Context as code](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TlC7jq4ooSM) · [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-1880,"y":1154,"width":360,"height":160,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"51138eaa43d22987","type":"text","text":"**Question-flurry planning**: Ask the agent to interrogate the idea and generate many clarifying questions to remove ambiguity early.\n\nSource: [Agentic coding workflow](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=goOZSXmrYQ4)","x":-710,"y":-610,"width":250,"height":230,"color":"4"},
		{"id":"658257b1780d56fd","type":"text","text":"This is a good idea and I tend not to do it. I typically do PRD spec plan and then just implement the plan Maybe I just have small enough PRDs typically that it can do it in phases. but I still see that frequently I do them in phases, the plans are in phases, even though I give it to an agent.","x":180,"y":-806,"width":379,"height":213}
	],
	"edges":[
